<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-11-27T21:13:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-11-27T21:13:00-05:00" n="729" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1266a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-11-27T21:13:00-05:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 27, 1911, 9:13 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>628. Press reports state that British Government has mined the River Tyne
                            and the Firth of Forth. Please investigate and report to Department. An
                            early reply is requested.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>